excerpt: "Those tiny crystals are a texture signal, not a flaw, and they can make an aged cheese feel electric."
---

The white flecks in aged cheddar are usually crunchy protein or amino acid crystals that form as the cheese matures. They are one reason aged cheeses feel more complex than younger, smoother blocks.

On a board, lean into that texture. Pair aged cheddar with crisp crackers, tart pickles, roasted almonds, or a fruit preserve that brings acidity.

If the cheese tastes balanced and smells clean, those crystals are part of the pleasure.
